The '''Christian Peace Conference''' ({{lang-cs|Křesťanská mírová konference}}) was an international organization based in [[Prague]] and founded in 1958 by [[Josef Hromádka]], a pastor who had spent the [[World War II|war years]] in the United States, moving back to [[Czechoslovakia]] when the war ended and [[Heinrich Vogel]], an evangelical theologian.<ref>Bekanntgabe von Verleihungen des Verdienstordens der Bundesrepublik Deutschland.'' In: ''Bundesanzeiger.'' Jg. 25, Nr. 103, 5. Juni 1973</ref> Hromádka was a member of the Bureau of the [[World Peace Council]].<ref>Roberts, E.T., [http://www.osaarchivum.org/files/holdings/300/8/3/text/17-1-95.shtml ''Communist Hold On "Christian" Peace Movement''] {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/67vUoatBc?url=http://www.osaarchivum.org/files/holdings/300/8/3/text/17-1-95.shtml |date=2012-05-25 }}, 1964</ref> He was not a [[Marxist]], but the Christian Peace Conference often endorsed positions taken by [[Eastern bloc]] governments.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=O4GGgAmzl3gC&pg=PA81&lpg=PA81&dq=josef+hromadka&source=bl&ots=YilR-ouPg5&sig=bMZTqjIa2a57Y5mSrCujmg6LGgE&hl=en&ei=FxiTTsmFN4qYhQe7w4EV&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=5&sqi=2&ved=0CD8Q6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=josef%20hromadka&f=false Ramet, S.P., ''Protestantism and Politics in Eastern Europe and Russia'', Duke University Press]</ref> It has been alleged to have received $210,000 from [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] sources.<ref name=staar>[https://books.google.com/books?id=Hvv7U15xCtMC&source=gbs_navlinks_s Richard Felix Staar, ''Foreign policies of the Soviet Union'', Hoover Press, 1991, ISBN 0-8179-9102-6, pp.79-88]</ref>
