{{Infobox book | name = Lethal Politics: Soviet Genocide and Mass Murder since 1917 | title_orig = | translator = | image = Lethal Politics.jpg | caption = | author = [[Rudolph Rummel|R.J. Rummel]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = United States | language = | series = | subject = [[Communism]], [[Soviet Union]], [[Totalitarianism]], [[Genocide]] | genre = [[Political history]] | publisher = [[Transaction Publishers]] | pub_date = 1990 | media_type = | pages = 268 | isbn = 0-88738-333-5 | oclc = | dewey = | congress = | preceded_by = | followed_by = }}
'''''Lethal Politics: Soviet Genocide and Mass Murder since 1917''''' is an influential {{fact|date=December 2017}} book by [[Rudolph Rummel|R.J. Rummel]], published by [[Transaction Publishers]] in 1990. The book examines [[Mass killings in the Soviet Union|genocides and mass murders perpetrated by the Soviet regime]] from the days of [[Vladimir Lenin]] until the last years of the [[Cold War]], with an emphasis on the [[Joseph Stalin]] regime.<ref>Review by Tamas Meszerics, ''Journal of Communist Studies'', 7(4), 1991, p. 579</ref><ref>Review by Geoffrey Swain, ''Slavonic and East European Review'', 69(4), 1991, p. 765-66</ref>
Rummel's central theory was that citizens of totalitarian, especially [[Marxist]] systems, were most likely to be killed by their government, whereas "democratic systems provide a path to peace, and universalizing them would eliminate war and minimize global, political violence."<ref>R.J. Rummel, Preface to Lethal Politics</ref>
==Bibliography== *[[Rudolph Rummel|R.J. Rummel]] (1990). ''Lethal Politics: Soviet Genocide and Mass Murder since 1917'', New Brunswick, [[Transaction Publishers]], {{ISBN|0-88738-333-5}}, {{ISBN|1-56000-887-3}}
