{{Infobox Institute |name=MapLight |image_name=MapLight Logo Partner sm.jpg|MapLight Logo Partner sm] |image width=225px |caption= |established=March 2005 |chairman= |head_label=President and Co-Founder |head=Daniel Newman |location=[[Berkeley, CA]] |website= {{URL|maplight.org}} }}
'''MapLight''' is a nonpartisan, nonprofit research organization that reveals and tracks the [[Political finance|influence of money in politics]] in the United States.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Phelan|first1=Sarah|title=Follow the pension reform money to Wisconsin|url=http://www.sfbg.com/politics/2011/04/26/follow-pension-reform-money-wisconsin|accessdate=7 July 2014|publisher=San Francisco Bay Guardian|date=2011-04-26}}</ref> The organization publishes a free public database linking money and politics data sources, including campaign contributions to politicians, how politicians vote on bills, and support and opposition to legislation. MapLight provides data on both campaign finance and [[Campaign finance in the United States#Sources of data|voting behavior]] in one database.
MapLight uses an in-house research team in addition to data sources that include the [[National Institute on Money in State Politics]], the [[Center for Responsive Politics]], and [[Govtrack]].
==Policy positions== MapLight advocates for [[Publicly funded elections|public funding of elections]] and increased [[Campaign finance reform in the United States|campaign finance regulations]]. MapLight expressed disagreement with the Supreme Court rulings ''[[Citizens United v. Federal Election Commission]]'' and ''[[McCutcheon v. Federal Election Commission]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=MapLight's statement on the McCutcheon v. FEC decision: Supreme Court decision "Puts American Democracy in Peril," Rules in Favor of More Money in Politics|url=http://maplight.org/mccutcheon|publisher=MapLight|accessdate=7 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Costa|first1=Jay|title=Daniel Newman: The Myths and Realities of Corruption: Citizens United, Two Years Later|url=http://maplight.org/citizens-united-two-years-later|publisher=MapLight|accessdate=7 July 2014}}</ref>
==Funding== MapLight's donors include the [[Sunlight Foundation]], [[Open Society Foundations]], [[MacArthur Foundation]], [[Ford Foundation]], and the [[Tides (organization)|Tides Foundation]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Foundation and Individual Funders|url=http://maplight.org/foundations-and-individuals|publisher=MapLight|accessdate=7 July 2014}}</ref> In June 2014, ''[[Politico]]'' reported that MapLight was a recipient of funding through the [[Democracy Alliance]], a network of liberal donors who coordinate their anonymous political giving.<ref name=vogel>{{cite news|last1=Vogel|first1=Kenneth|title=Inside the vast liberal conspiracy|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2014/06/inside-the-vast-liberal-conspiracy-108171.html|accessdate=24 June 2014|publisher=Politico|date=2014-06-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Spring 2014 Democracy Alliance Investment Recommendations|url=https://www.documentcloud.org/documents/1202744-da-portfolio2012-2014-042714.html#document/p1|publisher=Democracy Alliance|accessdate=24 June 2014}}</ref> According to the ''[[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]]'', in 2010 [[George Soros]] underwrote a joint project between MapLight and the [[Wisconsin Center for Investigative Journalism]] to highlight the influence of money in Wisconsin politics.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bice|first1=Daniel|title=Liberal billionaire helping fund media groups in Wisconsin|url=http://www.jsonline.com/watchdog/noquarter/127706658.html|accessdate=7 July 2014|publisher=Milwaukee Journal Sentinel|date=2011-08-14}}</ref>
